## Understand the Importance of Time and Space Complexity in Algorithm Design

## What is Time and Space Complexity?

When designing algorithms, it is crucial to consider:

- **Time Complexity:** How fast does the algorithm run as the input size grows?
- **Space Complexity:** How much memory does the algorithm need as the input size increases?

Both of these factors determine how efficient and scalable your algorithm is.

---

## Why is Time Complexity Important?

- Helps predict performance.
- Avoids algorithms that take too long for large inputs.
- Optimizes user experience by ensuring fast responses.

> **Example:**
> Searching in an array:
> - **Linear Search:** O(n)
> - **Binary Search (sorted array):** O(log n)

### Java Example: Linear vs. Binary Search
```java
// Linear Search: O(n)
int linearSearch(int[] arr, int target) {
  for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    if (arr[i] == target) return i;
  }
  return -1;
}

// Binary Search: O(log n) - Array must be sorted
int binarySearch(int[] arr, int target) {
  int left = 0, right = arr.length - 1;
  while (left <= right) {
    int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
    if (arr[mid] == target) return mid;
    if (arr[mid] < target) left = mid + 1;
    else right = mid - 1;
  }
  return -1;
}
```

## Understand the Structure and Types of Linked Lists and Basic Operations

## What is a Linked List?
- A **Linked List** is a linear data structure where elements (nodes) are connected using pointers.
- Each node contains:
  - **Data**: The value stored in the node.
  - **Next**: Reference to the next node in the list.

**Basic Node Structure:**

```java
class Node {
int data;
Node next;
Node(int data) {
this.data = data;
this.next = null;
}
}
```

---

## Types of Linked Lists

### 1. Singly Linked List
- Each node points to the next node.
- Traversal is one-directional.

### 2. Doubly Linked List
- Each node has two references: to the next and previous nodes.
- Allows traversal in both directions.

### 3. Circular Linked List
- Last node points back to the first node.
- Can be singly or doubly circular.

---

## Basic Operations on Linked Lists

### 1. Insertion at the Beginning
```java
Node head = null;
Node newNode = new Node(10);
newNode.next = head;
head = newNode;
```

### 2. Insertion at the End
```java
Node newNode = new Node(20);
if (head == null) {
head = newNode;
} else {
Node temp = head;
while (temp.next != null) {
temp = temp.next;
}
temp.next = newNode;
}
```

### 3. Deletion of a Node (by Value)
```java
int key = 10;
Node temp = head, prev = null;
// If head node holds the key
if (temp != null && temp.data == key) {
head = temp.next;
} else {
while (temp != null && temp.data != key) {
prev = temp;
temp = temp.next;
}
if (temp != null) {
prev.next = temp.next;
}
}
```

### 4. Traversal of the Linked List
```java
Node temp = head;
while (temp != null) {
System.out.print(temp.data + " ");
temp = temp.next;
}
// Output: Data of each node
```

### 5. Searching for an Element
```java
int target = 30;
Node temp = head;
boolean found = false;
while (temp != null) {
if (temp.data == target) {
found = true;
break;
}
temp = temp.next;
}
System.out.println(found ? "Element found" : "Element not found");
```

---

## Summary
- Linked Lists consist of nodes connected through pointers.
- Types include **Singly**, **Doubly**, and **Circular** Linked Lists.
- Common operations:
  - Insertion (beginning, end)
  - Deletion
  - Traversal
  - Search
- Linked Lists offer dynamic memory allocation, unlike arrays.
- Efficient insertions and deletions but slower random access.

## Perform Insertion, Deletion, and Traversal Operations on Linked Lists

## What is a Linked List?

A **Linked List** is a linear data structure where elements (nodes) are connected by pointers. Each node contains:
- **Data:** Value of the node.
- **Next:** Reference to the next node in the list.

```java
class Node {
 int data;
 Node next;

 Node(int data) {
 this.data = data;
 this.next = null;
 }
}
```

---

## Insertion Operations

### 1. Insertion at the Beginning

- Add a new node before the current head.

```java
Node newNode = new Node(10);
newNode.next = head;
head = newNode;
```

### 2. Insertion at the End

- Traverse to the last node and insert.

```java
Node newNode = new Node(20);
if (head == null) {
 head = newNode;
} else {
 Node temp = head;
 while (temp.next != null) {
 temp = temp.next;
 }
 temp.next = newNode;
}
```

### 3. Insertion at a Specific Position

- Insert after traversing to the desired position.

```java
int position = 2;
Node newNode = new Node(30);
Node temp = head;
for (int i = 0; i < position - 1 && temp != null; i++) {
 temp = temp.next;
}
if (temp != null) {
 newNode.next = temp.next;
 temp.next = newNode;
}
```

---

## Deletion Operations

### 1. Delete by Value

- Find the node and adjust pointers.

```java
int key = 10;
Node temp = head, prev = null;

if (temp != null && temp.data == key) {
 head = temp.next;
} else {
 while (temp != null && temp.data != key) {
 prev = temp;
 temp = temp.next;
 }
 if (temp != null) {
 prev.next = temp.next;
 }
}
```

### 2. Delete at a Specific Position

```java
int position = 2;
Node temp = head;

if (position == 0 && head != null) {
 head = head.next;
} else {
 for (int i = 0; temp != null && i < position - 1; i++) {
 temp = temp.next;
 }
 if (temp != null && temp.next != null) {
 temp.next = temp.next.next;
 }
}
```

---

## Traversal Operation

- Go through each node and print data.

```java
Node temp = head;
while (temp != null) {
 System.out.print(temp.data + " ");
 temp = temp.next;
}
// Output: Data of each node
```

---

## Summary

- **Insertion:** Add nodes at beginning, end, or specific positions.
- **Deletion:** Remove nodes by value or position.
- **Traversal:** Visit each node to access or display data.
- Linked Lists provide flexibility with dynamic memory allocation.

> Mastering these operations builds a strong foundation for working with complex data structures like stacks, queues, and graphs!

## Learn the Basics of Stacks, LIFO Principle, and Operations such as Push, Pop, and Peek



A **Stack** is a linear data structure that follows the **LIFO** principle:
- **LIFO:** Last In, First Out.
- The last element added is the first one to be removed.

Common real-world examples:
- Pile of plates.
- Undo operations in text editors.

---

## Stack Operations

### 1. Push (Insert Element)
- Add an element to the top of the stack.

```java
Stack stack = new Stack<>();
stack.push(10);
stack.push(20);
stack.push(30);
// Stack: [10, 20, 30]
```

### 2. Pop (Remove Element)
- Remove the top element from the stack.

```java
int removedElement = stack.pop();
System.out.println("Popped element: " + removedElement);
// Output: Popped element: 30
// Stack after pop: [10, 20]
```

### 3. Peek (View Top Element)
- View the top element without removing it.

```java
int topElement = stack.peek();
System.out.println("Top element: " + topElement);
// Output: Top element: 20
```

### 4. isEmpty (Check if Stack is Empty)
- Check whether the stack has elements.

```java
if (stack.isEmpty()) {
 System.out.println("Stack is empty");
} else {
 System.out.println("Stack is not empty");
}
```

### 5. Size (Get Stack Size)
- Get the number of elements in the stack.

```java
System.out.println("Stack size: " + stack.size());
```

---

## LIFO Principle Explained

- The last element **pushed** is the first one to be **popped**.
- Stack behaves like a container where additions and removals happen at one end (the top).

> **Example:**
> Push: 10 â†’ 20 â†’ 30
> Stack: [10, 20, 30]
> Pop: 30 (removed first)

---

## Summary

- **Stack** uses LIFO order for operations.
- **Push:** Add element to top.
- **Pop:** Remove element from top.
- **Peek:** View top element without removing.
- **isEmpty & size:** Useful utility methods.

> Stacks are widely used in function call management, expression evaluation, undo mechanisms, and more!

## Explore Real-World Applications of Stacks, Queues, and Hashing

## Applications of Stacks

Stacks follow the **LIFO (Last In, First Out)** principle.

### 1. Expression Evaluation
- Used to evaluate **infix, prefix, and postfix** expressions.
- Especially useful for parsing mathematical expressions and implementing calculators.

> **Example:** Convert infix to postfix and then evaluate.

```java
// Simplified postfix evaluation
Stack stack = new Stack<>();
for (String token : postfixExpression) {
 if (isNumber(token)) {
 stack.push(Integer.parseInt(token));
 } else {
 int b = stack.pop();
 int a = stack.pop();
 stack.push(applyOperator(a, b, token));
 }
}
int result = stack.pop();
```

### 2. Undo Mechanism in Text Editors
- Stacks store previous states.
- Each operation is pushed onto the stack.
- Undo pops the last state.

### 3. Syntax Parsing
- Compilers use stacks to check for balanced parentheses, braces, and brackets.

---

## Applications of Queues

Queues follow the **FIFO (First In, First Out)** principle.

### 1. Task Scheduling
- Operating systems use queues to manage process scheduling.
- Tasks are enqueued and executed in order.

> **Example:** CPU scheduling queue

```java
Queue taskQueue = new LinkedList<>();
taskQueue.add("Task1");
taskQueue.add("Task2");

while (!taskQueue.isEmpty()) {
 System.out.println("Processing: " + taskQueue.poll());
}
```

### 2. Printer Spooling
- Print jobs are stored in a queue.
- Jobs are processed in the order they arrive.

### 3. Breadth-First Search (BFS) in Graphs
- BFS uses a queue to explore nodes level by level.

---

## Applications of Hashing

Hashing provides **fast data access** and is widely used in many real-world applications.

### 1. Indexing in Databases
- Hashing helps in indexing database records for faster query performance.
- Speeds up lookups and retrieval operations.

### 2. Caching
- Hash tables (like HashMap) are used in caching frequently accessed data.
- Example: Web browsers cache pages.

### 3. Password Storage (with Salted Hashing)
- Passwords are stored as hashes for security.
- Even if the database is compromised, raw passwords remain secure.

> **Example:** Using Java's built-in hash code

```java
String password = "mySecurePassword";
int hashedPassword = password.hashCode();
System.out.println(hashedPassword);
```

### 4. Data Deduplication
- Hashing identifies duplicate data by comparing hash values.

---

## Summary

- **Stacks**: Ideal for expression evaluation, undo mechanisms, and syntax parsing.
- **Queues**: Best for task scheduling, print spooling, and BFS traversal.
- **Hashing**: Powers fast data access in indexing, caching, password storage, and more.

> Mastering these applications will help you build efficient, real-world solutions!

## Understand Graph Traversal Algorithms: Depth-First Search (DFS) and Breadth-First Search (BFS)

## What is Graph Traversal?

Graph traversal means visiting all the nodes (vertices) in a graph systematically.
Two popular algorithms for graph traversal are:
- **Depth-First Search (DFS)**
- **Breadth-First Search (BFS)**

Both algorithms help in searching, pathfinding, and exploring connected components.

---

## Depth-First Search (DFS)

- Explores as far as possible along each branch before backtracking.
- Can be implemented using **recursion** or an **explicit stack**.

### When to Use DFS:
- To explore all paths.
- For topological sorting.
- Detecting cycles in a graph.

> **Time Complexity:** O(V + E)
> **Space Complexity:** O(V) (for visited nodes and recursion stack)

**Java Example:**

```java
void dfs(int node, boolean[] visited, List<List<Integer>> adjList) {
 visited[node] = true;
 System.out.print(node + " ");

 for (int neighbor : adjList.get(node)) {
 if (!visited[neighbor]) {
 dfs(neighbor, visited, adjList);
 }
 }
}
```

---

## Breadth-First Search (BFS)

- Explores all neighbors at the current depth before moving to the next depth level.
- Implemented using a **queue**.

### When to Use BFS:
- Finding the shortest path in an unweighted graph.
- Level-order traversal.
- Checking graph connectivity.

> **Time Complexity:** O(V + E)
> **Space Complexity:** O(V) (for visited nodes and queue)

**Java Example:**

```java
void bfs(int startNode, List<List<Integer>> adjList) {
 boolean[] visited = new boolean[adjList.size()];
 Queue<Integer> queue = new LinkedList<>();

 queue.add(startNode);
 visited[startNode] = true;

 while (!queue.isEmpty()) {
 int node = queue.poll();
 System.out.print(node + " ");

 for (int neighbor : adjList.get(node)) {
 if (!visited[neighbor]) {
 queue.add(neighbor);
 visited[neighbor] = true;
 }
 }
 }
}
```

---

## Summary

- **DFS:** Uses Stack/Recursion; Best for exploring all paths, cycle detection.
- **BFS:** Uses Queue; Best for shortest path, level-order traversal.

> ðŸŒŸ **Tip:** Practice both DFS and BFS on different graph problems to master traversal techniques!

**Understanding DFS and BFS is key to solving many real-world graph problems!**

## Explore Divide-and-Conquer Sorting Algorithms: Merge Sort and Quick Sort

## What is Divide and Conquer?

Divide and Conquer is a powerful algorithm design paradigm that involves:
- **Divide:** Break the problem into smaller subproblems.
- **Conquer:** Solve each subproblem recursively.
- **Combine:** Merge the solutions to solve the original problem.

Sorting algorithms like **Merge Sort** and **Quick Sort** use this approach to efficiently sort data.

---

## Merge Sort

### How it Works:
1. Divide the array into two halves.
2. Recursively sort each half.
3. Merge the sorted halves.

### Time and Space Complexity:
- **Time Complexity:** O(n log n) (Best, Average, Worst)
- **Space Complexity:** O(n)
- **Stability:** âœ… Stable

> **Best for:** Large datasets where stability is required.

### Java Example: Merge Sort

```java
void mergeSort(int[] arr, int left, int right) {
 if (left < right) {
 int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;

 mergeSort(arr, left, mid);
 mergeSort(arr, mid + 1, right);

 merge(arr, left, mid, right);
 }
}

void merge(int[] arr, int left, int mid, int right) {
 int n1 = mid - left + 1;
 int n2 = right - mid;

 int[] L = new int[n1];
 int[] R = new int[n2];

 for (int i = 0; i < n1; i++) L[i] = arr[left + i];
 for (int j = 0; j < n2; j++) R[j] = arr[mid + 1 + j];

 int i = 0, j = 0, k = left;
 while (i < n1 && j < n2) {
 if (L[i] <= R[j]) arr[k++] = L[i++];
 else arr[k++] = R[j++];
 }

 while (i < n1) arr[k++] = L[i++];
 while (j < n2) arr[k++] = R[j++];
}
```

---

## Quick Sort

### How it Works:
1. Select a **pivot** element.
2. Partition the array: elements less than pivot go left, greater go right.
3. Recursively apply quicksort to the sub-arrays.

### Time and Space Complexity:
- **Time Complexity:**
  - Best/Average: O(n log n)
  - Worst: O(nÂ²) *(rare, happens if pivot is poorly chosen)*
- **Space Complexity:** O(log n)
- **Stability:** âŒ Unstable

> **Best for:** When in-place sorting is preferred and average performance matters.

### Java Example: Quick Sort

```java
void quickSort(int[] arr, int low, int high) {
 if (low < high) {
 int pi = partition(arr, low, high);

 quickSort(arr, low, pi - 1);
 quickSort(arr, pi + 1, high);
 }
}

int partition(int[] arr, int low, int high) {
 int pivot = arr[high];
 int i = (low - 1);
 for (int j = low; j < high; j++) {
 if (arr[j] < pivot) {
 i++;
 int temp = arr[i];
 arr[i] = arr[j];
 arr[j] = temp;
 }
 }

 int temp = arr[i + 1];
 arr[i + 1] = arr[high];
 arr[high] = temp;

 return i + 1;
}
```

---

## Summary

- **Merge Sort:**
  - Time Complexity: O(n log n) / O(n log n) / O(n log n)
  - Space Complexity: O(n)
  - Stability: Stable

- **Quick Sort:**
  - Time Complexity: O(n log n) / O(n log n) / O(nÂ²)
  - Space Complexity: O(log n)
  - Stability: Unstable

> ðŸš€ **Tip:** Merge Sort guarantees performance, while Quick Sort is faster in practice with good pivot selection.

---

> ðŸ” **Explore both algorithms with different datasets to understand their behavior better!**

## Understand Advanced Algorithms: Heap Sort and Interpolation Search

## What are Advanced Algorithms?

Advanced algorithms provide more efficient solutions for complex problems, especially with large datasets. Two powerful algorithms in this category are:
- **Heap Sort**
- **Interpolation Search**

---

## Heap Sort

### How it Works:
- Builds a **max-heap** from the input data.
- Repeatedly extracts the maximum element from the heap and rebuilds the heap until all elements are sorted.

### Time and Space Complexity:
- **Time Complexity:** O(n log n)
- **Space Complexity:** O(1) (in-place)

> **Best for:** When you need consistent O(n log n) performance and in-place sorting.

### Java Example: Heap Sort

```java
void heapify(int[] arr, int n, int i) {
 int largest = i;
 int left = 2 * i + 1;
 int right = 2 * i + 2;

 if (left < n && arr[left] > arr[largest]) largest = left;
 if (right < n && arr[right] > arr[largest]) largest = right;

 if (largest != i) {
 int swap = arr[i];
 arr[i] = arr[largest];
 arr[largest] = swap;

 heapify(arr, n, largest);
 }
}

void heapSort(int[] arr) {
 int n = arr.length;

 for (int i = n / 2 - 1; i >= 0; i--) heapify(arr, n, i);

 for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
 int temp = arr[0];
 arr[0] = arr[i];
 arr[i] = temp;

 heapify(arr, i, 0);
 }
}
```

---

## Interpolation Search

### How it Works:
- Assumes data is uniformly distributed.
- Estimates the position of the target using the formula:

```java
npos = low + ((target - arr[low]) * (high - low) / (arr[high] - arr[low]));
```

- Faster than Binary Search for uniformly distributed data.

### Time and Space Complexity:
- **Time Complexity:** O(log log n) (best case), O(n) (worst case)
- **Space Complexity:** O(1)

> **Best for:** Large, sorted, uniformly distributed datasets.

### Java Example: Interpolation Search

```java
int interpolationSearch(int[] arr, int target) {
 int low = 0, high = arr.length - 1;

 while (low <= high && target >= arr[low] && target <= arr[high]) {
 if (low == high) {
 if (arr[low] == target) return low;
 return -1;
 }

 int pos = low + ((target - arr[low]) * (high - low)) / (arr[high] - arr[low]);

 if (arr[pos] == target) return pos;
 if (arr[pos] < target) low = pos + 1;
 else high = pos - 1;
 }

 return -1;
}
```

---

## Summary

- **Heap Sort:**
  - Time Complexity: O(n log n)
  - Space Complexity: O(1)
  - When to Use: Consistent performance, in-place sorting

- **Interpolation Search:**
  - Time Complexity: O(log log n) (best), O(n) (worst)
  - Space Complexity: O(1)
  - When to Use: Sorted & uniformly distributed datasets

> ðŸš€ **Tip:** Choose algorithms based on your data characteristics and performance needs!

---

> **Practice implementing both to strengthen your understanding of advanced algorithms.**

## Dynamic Programming Problems

## What is Dynamic Programming (DP)?

Dynamic Programming is an optimization technique used to solve complex problems by breaking them down into simpler subproblems and storing the results of subproblems to avoid redundant work.

### Key Concepts:
- **Overlapping Subproblems:** Same subproblems are solved multiple times.
- **Optimal Substructure:** Solutions to subproblems help form the solution to the overall problem.

---

## Problem 1: Longest Common Subsequence (LCS)

- **Goal:** Find the length of the longest subsequence common to two sequences.
- **Approach:** Use a 2D DP table to store lengths of LCS for substrings.

### DP Formula:
```java
if (text1[i] == text2[j])
 dp[i][j] = 1 + dp[i-1][j-1];
else
 dp[i][j] = max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]);
```

### Java Example:
```java
int lcs(String text1, String text2) {
 int m = text1.length(), n = text2.length();
 int[][] dp = new int[m + 1][n + 1];

 for (int i = 1; i <= m; i++) {
 for (int j = 1; j <= n; j++) {
 if (text1.charAt(i - 1) == text2.charAt(j - 1))
 dp[i][j] = 1 + dp[i - 1][j - 1];
 else
 dp[i][j] = Math.max(dp[i - 1][j], dp[i][j - 1]);
 } }
 return dp[m][n];
}
```

---

## Problem 2: Matrix Chain Multiplication

- **Goal:** Find the most efficient way to multiply a given sequence of matrices.
- **Approach:** Try all possible parenthesizations and store minimum multiplication cost.

### DP Formula:
```java
dp[i][j] = min(dp[i][k] + dp[k+1][j] + cost of multiplying the two parts)
```

### Java Example:
```java
int matrixChainOrder(int[] dims) {
 int n = dims.length - 1;
 int[][] dp = new int[n][n];

 for (int len = 2; len <= n; len++) {
 for (int i = 0; i <= n - len; i++) {
 int j = i + len - 1;
 dp[i][j] = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
 for (int k = i; k < j; k++) {
 int cost = dp[i][k] + dp[k + 1][j] + dims[i] * dims[k + 1] * dims[j + 1];
 dp[i][j] = Math.min(dp[i][j], cost);
 } }
 } }
 return dp[0][n - 1];
}
```

---

## Problem 3: 0/1 Knapsack Problem

- **Goal:** Maximize total value without exceeding weight capacity.
- **Approach:** Use DP to choose between including or excluding each item.

### DP Formula:
```java
if (weight[i] <= capacity)
 dp[i][w] = max(dp[i-1][w], dp[i-1][w - weight[i]] + value[i]);
else
 dp[i][w] = dp[i-1][w];
```

### Java Example:
```java
int knapsack(int[] weight, int[] value, int capacity) {
 int n = weight.length;
 int[][] dp = new int[n + 1][capacity + 1];

 for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
 for (int w = 0; w <= capacity; w++) {
 if (weight[i - 1] <= w)
 dp[i][w] = Math.max(dp[i - 1][w], dp[i - 1][w - weight[i - 1]] + value[i - 1]);
 else
 dp[i][w] = dp[i - 1][w];
 } }
 return dp[n][capacity];
}
```

---

## Summary

- **Longest Common Subsequence:** 2D DP Table.
- **Matrix Chain Multiplication:** Recursive + DP Table.
- **0/1 Knapsack Problem:** Iterative DP with weight check.

> **Tip:** Break problems into subproblems and store solutions to avoid redundant calculations!

---

> **Practice these problems to master dynamic programming techniques!**

## Explore Ways to Style Links and Create Navigation Menus

Links can be styled to make them visually appealing and to match the design of your website. You can also combine links to create navigation menus.

---

## Styling Links with CSS

### Change Link Color
```html
<a href="https://example.com">Visit Example</a>
```
```html
<style>
a {
  color: blue; /* Change text color */
}
</style>
```

### Remove Underline
```html
<style>
a {
  text-decoration: none; /* Removes underline */
}
</style>
```

### Change Link on Hover
```html
<style>
a:hover {
  color: red; /* Change color when mouse hovers */
  text-decoration: underline;
}
</style>
```

### Different States of Links
```html
<style>
a:link {
  color: blue; /* Unvisited link */
}

a:visited {
  color: purple; /* Visited link */
}

a:hover {
  color: red; /* Hover effect */
}

a:active {
  color: green; /* Active link (when clicked) */
}
</style>
```

---

## Creating Navigation Menus

### Simple Horizontal Navigation Menu
```html
<nav>
  <a href="#home">Home</a>
  <a href="#services">Services</a>
  <a href="#contact">Contact</a>
</nav>
```
```html
<style>
nav {
  background-color: #333;
  padding: 10px;
}

nav a {
  color: white;
  text-decoration: none;
  margin: 0 15px;
}

nav a:hover {
  text-decoration: underline;
}
</style>
```

### Vertical Navigation Menu (Using Lists)
```html
<nav>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="#home">Home</a></li>
    <li><a href="#services">Services</a></li>
    <li><a href="#contact">Contact</a></li>
  </ul>
</nav>
```
```html
<style>
nav ul {
  list-style-type: none;
  padding: 0;
}

nav ul li {
  margin: 10px 0;
}

nav ul li a {
  text-decoration: none;
  color: #333;
}

nav ul li a:hover {
  color: #007BFF;
}
</style>
